Polynomial Regression Analysis
UCI Auto MPG Dataset
IEEE SSCS | AI Sub-Team | Session 6
1. Introduction & Dataset Overview
This report documents a full polynomial regression study on the UCI Auto MPG dataset. The goal is to predict a car's fuel efficiency (miles per gallon MPG) from physical features, with a focus on diagnosing overfitting, applying regularization, and selecting the right model complexity.

1.1 Dataset
•	Source: UCI Machine Learning Repository Auto MPG
•	398 rows × 9 columns (after dropping 6 rows with missing horsepower values: 392 usable)
•	Target variable: mpg (continuous, right-skewed)
•	Primary predictor used: horsepower (strongest single-feature correlation with MPG)

1.2 Key EDA Findings
•	MPG is right-skewed: most cars cluster between 10-30 MPG with a tail toward higher efficiency.
•	Horsepower and weight are strongly negatively correlated with MPG (r ≈ −0.78 and -0.83 respectively).
•	Displacement and cylinders are highly correlated with each other multicollinearity exists in the full feature set.
•	No outliers were removed; the dataset is clean after dropping the 6 NaN rows.
2. Methodology
2.1 Workflow
The analysis followed these steps in order:
•	Data loading and EDA (distributions, scatter plots, correlation heatmap)
•	80/20 train-test split (random_state=42) all models trained on the same split
•	Linear baseline (degree 1) as the benchmark
•	Polynomial feature expansion at degrees 2, 3, 4, and 5
•	Regularization: Ridge (L2) and Lasso (L1) at degree 3 via GridSearchCV
•	Residual analysis on the best model (Ridge, degree 3)

2.2 Pipeline Design
Each polynomial model uses a scikit-learn Pipeline: PolynomialFeatures → StandardScaler → LinearRegression (or Ridge/Lasso). Scaling is critical because polynomial features vary wildly in magnitude (e.g., horsepower² vs horsepower⁵).
3. Regression Metrics Definitions & When to Use
Five metrics were computed for every model. The table below explains each one, when it is most useful, and its key limitations.

Metric	Full Name	When to Use / Limitations	Direction
MSE	Mean Squared Error	Penalises large errors heavily due to squaring. Sensitive to outliers. Use when large errors are especially costly.	Low is better
MAE	Mean Absolute Error	Average absolute difference. More robust to outliers than MSE. Easy to interpret in target units.	Low is better
RMSE	Root Mean Squared Error	√MSE — same unit as target (MPG). Most interpretable for regression. Preferred for comparing models.	Low is better
MAPE	Mean Abs. % Error	Relative error as percentage. Scale-free, great for stakeholder communication. Undefined when y = 0.	Low is better
R²	Coefficient of Determination	Fraction of variance explained by the model (0–1). 1 = perfect. Can be negative for very bad models.	High is better

For this task predicting MPG in a real physical unit RMSE is the most informative metric because it is in the same unit as the target (MPG) and penalises large mispredictions more than MAE. MAPE is useful for communicating results to non-technical stakeholders. R² gives a quick sense of 'how much of the variance did we explain?'
