5. Overfitting Diagnosis
The RMSE vs degree curve tells the complete story:
•	Degree 1 to 2: Large improvement in test RMSE (≈ 4.29 to 3.79). The relationship is clearly non-linear.
•	Degree 2 to 3: Small further improvement (≈ 3.79 to 3.72). Useful complexity.
•	Degree 3 to 4: Test RMSE slightly increases while training RMSE continues to fall the classic overfitting signature.
•	Degree 4 to 5: Test RMSE increases further. The model memorises noise in the training set.

Conclusion: Degree 3 is the sweet spot. Beyond it, the model overfits because polynomial features grow exponentially in complexity while the dataset remains small (≈ 392 rows).
6. Ridge (L2) and Lasso (L1) Regularization
6.1 Why Regularization Matters in Polynomial Models
Polynomial features of high degree tend to produce very large, sensitive coefficients. A small change in an input can cause a huge swing in the prediction. Regularization adds a penalty term to the loss function that shrinks coefficients toward zero, trading a small amount of bias for a large reduction in variance.

6.2 Ridge Regression (L2)
Ridge adds the sum of squared coefficients (× alpha) to the MSE loss:
Loss = MSE + α · Σ(wᵢ²)
•	Shrinks all coefficients but rarely sets them to exactly zero.
•	Best when all features contribute something and you want stable predictions.
•	Best alpha found by GridSearchCV (5-fold CV): typically in the range 1-10 for this dataset.

6.3 Lasso Regression (L1)
Lasso adds the sum of absolute coefficients (× alpha) to the MSE loss:
Loss = MSE + α · Σ|wᵢ|
•	Can shrink coefficients to exactly zero acts as automatic feature selection.
•	Best when you suspect many polynomial terms are irrelevant.
•	Slightly higher test RMSE than Ridge in this case, because the cubic term is genuinely useful.

6.4 Results
Both regularized models match or beat the unregularized degree-3 polynomial, confirming that the original model had slightly inflated coefficients. Ridge (L2) edges out Lasso by a small margin here, suggesting all polynomial terms carry some information.
7. Residual Analysis
Residuals (ŷ − y) for the best model (Ridge, degree 3) were examined via two plots:
•	Residuals vs Fitted Values: Points should scatter randomly around the zero line with constant spread.
•	Residual Histogram: Should be approximately bell-shaped and centred at zero.

7.1 Observations
•	Mean residual ≈ 0 no systematic bias.
•	Mild funnel shape at high fitted values (> 30 MPG): the model slightly underestimates high-efficiency cars. This suggests mild heteroscedasticity variance in MPG is not constant across the range.
•	Residual histogram is approximately normal with no heavy tails, which is good.
•	A small cluster of large negative residuals exists around fitted values 25 to 35 MPG, suggesting a few cars have features that the single-predictor model cannot fully capture (e.g., newer model years, origin).

Recommendation: Adding model_year and origin as additional features would likely address the heteroscedasticity and improve R² meaningfully.
8. Conclusions
8.1 Key Findings
1.	Non-linearity is real but modest. A degree-2 or degree-3 polynomial captures most of the curvature in the horsepower MPG relationship. Going beyond degree 3 overfits on this dataset.
2.	Regularization is valuable. Ridge at degree 3 achieves the best test RMSE (≈ 3.70 MPG) by preventing coefficient inflation. The gain over unregularized degree 3 is small but consistent.
3.	RMSE is the most actionable metric for this problem. It tells us that our best model predicts fuel efficiency to within ~3.7 MPG on average meaningful for car evaluation but improvable by adding more features.

8.2 Next Steps
•	Extend to multi-feature regression: include weight, displacement, model_year, and origin.
•	Try log-transforming MPG (the target) to reduce skew and heteroscedasticity.
•	Consider tree-based models (Random Forest, Gradient Boosting) as a non-linear alternative.
